    "heading": "event-kinds",
    "content": "`user_message`"
  }, {
    "heading": "event-kinds",
    "content": "A message authored by the end user."
  }, {
    "heading": "event-kinds",
    "content": "`assistant_message`"
  }, {
    "heading": "event-kinds",
    "content": "A reply generated by your AI."
  }, {
    "heading": "event-kinds",
    "content": "`tool_result`"
  }, {
    "heading": "event-kinds",
    "content": "Output from a tool/function call your assistant made."
  }, {
    "heading": "event-kinds",
    "content": "`app_event`"
  }, {
    "heading": "event-kinds",
    "content": "Anything else — domain events, lifecycle events, custom signals."
  }, {
    "heading": "when-do-events-show-up-in-search",
    "content": "Never, directly. Search always returns **memories**, not events. If you want the original source events alongside results, pass `include_source_events=True` to `search()`."
  }, {
    "heading": "memories-the-extracted-output",
    "content": "A **memory** is something Memsy has distilled from one or more events — a stable fact about an actor or session, written in natural language, embedded into a vector space, and indexed for semantic retrieval. You don't create memories directly; Memsy creates them from your events."
  }, {
    "heading": "memories-the-extracted-output",
    "content": "In the SDK a memory surfaces as a `SearchResult`:"
  }, {
    "heading": "typical-flow",
    "content": "Events are cheap to produce; memories are created lazily. That's why `ingest()` returns immediately while `search()` reads from the processed index."
  }, {
    "heading": "next",
    "content": "How actors and sessions scope your data → **Actors and Sessions**."
  }, {
    "heading": "next",
    "content": "Why ingest is async → **Async Processing**."
